            "answer_text": "Of course! Has any large human population not engaged in atrocities against other groups? However, this topic is related to scale, timeline, location, etc. In this regard, it is still no different than all other populations that engaged in atrocities (or, will engage in them in the future). I\u2019ll give you an example\u2026 Vikings. Pretty brutal people right? Well, this was a northern Germanic group that exploded on the world stage at a specific time and place. They had a warrior culture that valued death in battle and had no moral qualms about killing and plundering. That was part of their overrall world view. However, fast forward a bit through Viking history, and these Norsemen would accept new religious beliefs, mix with different people, and morph into new nations\u2026and actually become a new people. They aren\u2019t static. So, as we go on this theoretical journey and arrive at the present time, we find the \u201cVikings\u201d - or, rather\u2026their descendants. And these Norsemen might call themselves Swedes, or Norwegians, or Icelanders, etc. And these Nordic countries are some of the most liberal and stable nations on the earth. Although, to digress a little bit. Perhaps they took the radical progressive politics a bit too far and now they\u2019ve imported \u201cheathens\u201d from other countries at such high rates, that they are establishing new cultural norms and are tearing down society a bit. But, that is a completely different topic. Back to the Native American atrocity thing\u2026 Look, the other thing to realize is that there are hundreds of tribes in the Americas. Some were more warlike or brutal than others. Heck, some were not warlike at all. And many tribes just maintained a defensive posture against more aggressive neighbors. So, it really depends on what group you are talking about. It would be like asking, \u201cDid Africans commit atrocities against other tribes?\u201d That is a huge continent, and you\u2019d be lumping a lot of distinct cultures and populations together under one umbrella term. It is not very specific. Same goes with this Native question. Who are you talking about here? ",
