            },
            "answer_text": "Original question \u201cDid Native Americans commit genocide on other native Americans?\u201d, was merged with \u201cDid Native Americans commit atrocities against other tribes?\u201d on 4/28/2018. First, a reply I made to post answering the first: \u201cGenocide, rare, and more slow and incidental than fully intended; But, massacres\u2014less frequent in the Americas more owing to geography and logistics. One regional example, touching on repeat patterns: \u201cMesa of Sorrows\u201d by James F. Brooks.\u201d For the Southwest region of North America, I recommend James F. Brooks work, having attended a presentation at the University of Arizona Book Fair a few years ago, featuring him, an archaeologist, and a Hopi man who served both as a counselor and as a tribal historian. The latter said that emotions from the massacre of Avat\u2019ovi carried through several centuries to the present, presenting even now as PTSD similar to what he sees from abusive family situations. For definitions: \u201cgenocide\u201d as at least attempted wiping out of a group with its own language; \u201cmassacre\u201d as more than a battle, but killing of more helpless people. ",
