                "name": "Anna Demers",
                "href": "/profile/Anna-Demers"
            },
            "answer_text": "Yes they have. My great grandmother was Wendat from the turtle clan. ( Huron is the most common name given to them by the French that came to Canada in early 1600\u2019s) She passed along this story of the 100 year war between the Wendat tribe and the Mohawk tribe. It was all intermingled with the French and the British that came to Canada during that time. Hurons and Mowhawks had some peace agreements but it was a rocky relationship because they competed for the lands that assured survival. They would regularly ambush each other\u2019s villages. My great grandmother spoke of the young Mohawk men coming of age coming to attack her village and they would scalp some of their victims. It was like a trophy to them. After that, they would leave and go back to where they came from. She also stated that the children were not killed during an ambush. Instead, they were brought back to their respective villages and adopted by the members of the tribe. The children were raised as their own. I do not know why this was done but my great grandmother stated this. Please note that the Hurons sided with the French and the Mohawks sided with the British. Before that, they were at war with each other and it was called the 100 year war. Below is a source the seems to confirm what my great grandmother stated. The French created war between the Iroquois and New France from 1609 to 1701. It was a 92-year war with us. They lost every one and sued for peace to end the wars. The Great Peace of Montreal was made on June 25th 1701, on the summer solstice. Source: Mohawk Nation News Below is an other source that gives an other interesting perspective. The beaver war. Our Proud History ",
